<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Iowa State University</h1> <div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div> <div id="contentSub"></div>
<div id="jump-to-nav"></div> <a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">Jump to navigation</a>
<a class="mw-jump-link" href="#p-search">Jump to search</a>
<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">"Iowa State" redirects here. For the state, see <a href="/wiki/Iowa" title="Iowa">Iowa</a>.</div>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Not to be confused with <a href="/wiki/University_of_Iowa" title="University of Iowa">University of Iowa</a>.</div>

<p><b>Iowa State University of Science and Technology</b>, generally referred to as <b>Iowa State</b>, is a co-flagship and public <a href="/wiki/Land-grant_university" title="Land-grant university">land-grant</a> and <a href="/wiki/Space_grant_colleges" class="mw-redirect" title="Space grant colleges">space-grant</a> <a href="/wiki/Research_university" title="Research university">research university</a> located in <a href="/wiki/Ames,_Iowa" title="Ames, Iowa">Ames</a>, <a href="/wiki/Iowa" title="Iowa">Iowa</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a>. It is the largest university in the state of Iowa and the third largest university in the <a href="/wiki/Big_12_Conference" title="Big 12 Conference">Big 12 athletic conference</a>. Iowa State is <a href="/wiki/Carnegie_Classification_of_Institutions_of_Higher_Education" title="Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education">classified</a> as a research university with "highest research activity" by the <a href="/wiki/Carnegie_Foundation_for_the_Advancement_of_Teaching" title="Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching">Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Carnegie_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Carnegie-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Iowa State is also a member of the <a href="/wiki/Association_of_American_Universities" title="Association of American Universities">Association of American Universities</a> (AAU), which consists of 60 leading research universities in North America.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Founded in 1858 and <a href="/wiki/Coeducational" class="mw-redirect" title="Coeducational">coeducational</a> from its start, Iowa State became the nation’s first designated land-grant institution when the <a href="/wiki/Iowa_Legislature" class="mw-redirect" title="Iowa Legislature">Iowa Legislature</a> accepted the provisions of the 1862 <a href="/wiki/Morrill_Land-Grant_Colleges_Act" class="mw-redirect" title="Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act">Morrill Act</a> on September 11, 1862, making Iowa the first state in the nation to do so.<sup id="cite_ref-point_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-point-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Iowa State's academic offerings are administered today through eight colleges, including the graduate college, that offer over 100 bachelor's degree programs, 112 master's degree programs, and 83 at the Ph.D. level, plus a professional degree program in <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State_University_College_of_Veterinary_Medicine" title="Iowa State University College of Veterinary Medicine">Veterinary Medicine</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Iowa State University's athletic teams, the <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State_Cyclones" title="Iowa State Cyclones">Cyclones</a>, compete in <a href="/wiki/NCAA_Division_I" title="NCAA Division I">Division I</a> of the <a href="/wiki/NCAA" class="mw-redirect" title="NCAA">NCAA</a> and are a founding member of the <a href="/wiki/Big_12_Conference" title="Big 12 Conference">Big 12 Conference</a>. The Cyclones field 16 varsity teams and have won numerous NCAA national championships.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Beginnings">Beginnings</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Beginnings">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In 1856, the <a href="/wiki/Iowa_General_Assembly" title="Iowa General Assembly">Iowa General Assembly</a> enacted legislation to establish the Iowa Agricultural College and <a href="/wiki/Model_farm" title="Model farm">Model Farm</a>. This institution (now Iowa State University) was officially established on March 22, 1858, by the General Assembly. <a href="/wiki/Story_County,_Iowa" title="Story County, Iowa">Story County</a> was chosen as the location on June 21, 1859, beating proposals from <a href="/wiki/Johnson_County,_Iowa" title="Johnson County, Iowa">Johnson</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kossuth_County,_Iowa" title="Kossuth County, Iowa">Kossuth</a>, <a href="/wiki/Marshall_County,_Iowa" title="Marshall County, Iowa">Marshall</a> and <a href="/wiki/Polk_County,_Iowa" title="Polk County, Iowa">Polk</a> counties. The original farm of 648 acres (2.62&#160;km<sup>2</sup>) was purchased for a cost of $5,379.<sup id="cite_ref-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:AdonijahWelch.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/AdonijahWelch.jpg/170px-AdonijahWelch.jpg" width="170" height="197" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/AdonijahWelch.jpg/255px-AdonijahWelch.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/15/AdonijahWelch.jpg 2x" data-file-width="300" data-file-height="348" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:AdonijahWelch.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Adonijah_Welch" title="Adonijah Welch">Adonijah Welch</a>, ISU's first president</div></div></div>
<p>Iowa was the first state in the nation to accept the provisions of the <a href="/wiki/Morrill_Act_of_1862" class="mw-redirect" title="Morrill Act of 1862">Morrill Act of 1862</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Pres_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pres-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> Iowa subsequently designated Iowa State as the <a href="/wiki/Land-grant_college" class="mw-redirect" title="Land-grant college">land-grant college</a> on March 29, 1864.<sup id="cite_ref-point_6-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-point-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Pres_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pres-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> From the start, Iowa Agricultural College focused on the ideals that higher education should be accessible to all and that the university should teach liberal and practical subjects. These ideals are integral to the land-grant university.<sup id="cite_ref-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874_8-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The institution was coeducational from the first preparatory class admitted in 1868. The formal admitting of students began the following year, and the first graduating class of 1872 consisted of 24 men and two women.<sup id="cite_ref-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874_8-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The Farm House, the first building on the Iowa State campus, was completed in 1861 before the campus was occupied by students or classrooms. It became the home of the superintendent of the Model Farm and in later years, the deans of Agriculture, including Seaman Knapp and "Tama Jim" Wilson. Iowa State's first president, <a href="/wiki/Adonijah_Welch" title="Adonijah Welch">Adonijah Welch</a>, briefly stayed at the Farm House and penned his inaugural speech in a second floor bedroom.<sup id="cite_ref-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874_8-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The college's first farm tenants primed the land for agricultural experimentation. The Iowa Experiment Station was one of the university's prominent features. Practical courses of instruction were taught, including one designed to give a general training for the career of a farmer. Courses in <a href="/wiki/Mechanical_engineering" title="Mechanical engineering">mechanical</a>, <a href="/wiki/Civil_engineering" title="Civil engineering">civil</a>, <a href="/wiki/Electrical_engineering" title="Electrical engineering">electrical</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Mining_engineering" title="Mining engineering">mining engineering</a> were also part of the curriculum.
</p><p>In 1870, President Welch and I. P. Robert, professor of agriculture, held three-day farmers' institutes at <a href="/wiki/Cedar_Falls,_Iowa" title="Cedar Falls, Iowa">Cedar Falls</a>, <a href="/wiki/Council_Bluffs,_Iowa" title="Council Bluffs, Iowa">Council Bluffs</a>, <a href="/wiki/Washington,_Iowa" title="Washington, Iowa">Washington</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Muscatine,_Iowa" title="Muscatine, Iowa">Muscatine</a>. These became the earliest institutes held off-campus by a land grant institution and were the forerunners of 20th century extension.
</p><p>In 1872, the first courses were given in domestic economy (home economics, family and consumer sciences) and were taught by Mary B. Welch, the president's wife. Iowa State became the first land grant university in the nation to offer training in domestic economy for college credit.<sup id="cite_ref-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874_8-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1858–1874-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 1879, the "School" of Veterinary Science was organized, the first state veterinary college in the United States (although veterinary courses has been taught since the beginning of the College). This was originally a two-year course leading to a diploma. The veterinary course of study contained classes in zoology, botany, anatomy of domestic animals, veterinary obstetrics, and sanitary science.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Iowa_state_beardshear_hall.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Iowa_state_beardshear_hall.jpg/220px-Iowa_state_beardshear_hall.jpg" width="220" height="137" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Iowa_state_beardshear_hall.jpg/330px-Iowa_state_beardshear_hall.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Iowa_state_beardshear_hall.jpg/440px-Iowa_state_beardshear_hall.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1280" data-file-height="799" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Iowa_state_beardshear_hall.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Beardshear Hall</div></div></div>
<p>William M. Beardshear was appointed President of Iowa State in 1891. During his tenure, Iowa Agricultural College truly came of age. Beardshear developed new agricultural programs and was instrumental in hiring premier faculty members such Anson Marston, Louis B. Spinney, J.B. Weems, Perry G. Holden, and Maria Roberts. He also expanded the university administration, and the following buildings were added to the campus: Morrill Hall (1891); the Campanile (1899); Old Botany (now Carrie Chapman Catt Hall) (1892); and Margaret Hall (1895) which continue to stand today. In his honor, Iowa State named its central administrative building (Central Building) after Beardshear in 1925.<sup id="cite_ref-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1900–1924_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1900–1924-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> In 1898, reflecting the school's growth during his tenure, it was renamed Iowa State College of Agricultural and Mechanic Arts, or Iowa State for short.
</p><p>Today, Beardshear Hall holds the following offices: President, Vice-President, Treasurer, Secretary, Registrar, Provost, and student financial aid. Catt Hall is named after famed alumna <a href="/wiki/Carrie_Chapman_Catt" title="Carrie Chapman Catt">Carrie Chapman Catt</a> and is the home of the College of Liberal Arts and Sciences.
</p>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Isubeardshear2008.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/Isubeardshear2008.jpg/170px-Isubeardshear2008.jpg" width="170" height="227" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/Isubeardshear2008.jpg/255px-Isubeardshear2008.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/Isubeardshear2008.jpg/340px-Isubeardshear2008.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2304" data-file-height="3072" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Isubeardshear2008.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Beardshear Hall celebrating Sesquicentennial in 2008</div></div></div>
<p>In 1912 Iowa State had its first Homecoming celebration. The idea was first proposed by Professor Samuel Beyer, the college’s “patron saint of athletics,” who suggested that Iowa State inaugurate a celebration for alumni during the annual football game against rival University of Iowa. Iowa State’s new president, Raymond A. Pearson, liked the idea and issued a special invitation to alumni two weeks prior to the event: “We need you, we must have you. Come and see what a school you have made in Iowa State College. Find a way.” In October 2012 Iowa State marked its 100th Homecoming with a "<a href="/wiki/Cy_the_Cardinal" title="Cy the Cardinal">CYtennial</a>" Celebration.<sup id="cite_ref-History_of_Iowa_State_Homecoming_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-History_of_Iowa_State_Homecoming-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Iowa State celebrated its first <a href="/wiki/VEISHEA" title="VEISHEA">VEISHEA</a> on May 11–13, 1922. Wallace McKee (class of 1922) served as the first chairman of the Central Committee and Frank D. Paine (professor of electrical engineering) chose the name, based on the first letters of Iowa State's colleges: Veterinary Medicine, Engineering, Industrial Science, Home Economics, and Agriculture. VEISHEA grew to become the largest student-run festival in the nation.<sup id="cite_ref-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1900–1924_12-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-of_Iowa_State_Time_Line,_1900–1924-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The Statistical Laboratory was established in 1933, with George W. Snedecor, professor of mathematics, as the first director. It was and is the first research and consulting institute of its kind in the country.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>While attempting to develop a faster method of computation, mathematics and physics professor <a href="/wiki/John_Vincent_Atanasoff" title="John Vincent Atanasoff">John Vincent Atanasoff</a> conceptualized the basic tenets of what would become the world’s first electronic digital computer, the <a href="/wiki/Atanasoff-Berry_Computer" class="mw-redirect" title="Atanasoff-Berry Computer">Atanasoff-Berry Computer</a> (ABC), during a drive to <a href="/wiki/Illinois" title="Illinois">Illinois</a> in 1937. These included the use of a binary system of arithmetic, the separation of computer and memory functions, and regenerative drum memory, among others. The 1939 prototype was constructed with graduate student <a href="/wiki/Clifford_Berry" title="Clifford Berry">Clifford Berry</a> in the basement of the Physics Building.<sup id="cite_ref-auto_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>During <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a>, Iowa State was one of 131 colleges and universities nationally that took part in the <a href="/wiki/V-12_Navy_College_Training_Program" title="V-12 Navy College Training Program">V-12 Navy College Training Program</a> which offered students a path to a Navy commission.<sup id="cite_ref-iowastate-v-12_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-iowastate-v-12-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Maturity_as_a_university">Maturity as a university</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Maturity as a university">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Catt_Hall,_previously_known_as_Agriculture_Hall,_at_Iowa_State_University.JPG" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Catt_Hall%2C_previously_known_as_Agriculture_Hall%2C_at_Iowa_State_University.JPG/220px-Catt_Hall%2C_previously_known_as_Agriculture_Hall%2C_at_Iowa_State_University.JPG" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Catt_Hall%2C_previously_known_as_Agriculture_Hall%2C_at_Iowa_State_University.JPG/330px-Catt_Hall%2C_previously_known_as_Agriculture_Hall%2C_at_Iowa_State_University.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Catt_Hall%2C_previously_known_as_Agriculture_Hall%2C_at_Iowa_State_University.JPG/440px-Catt_Hall%2C_previously_known_as_Agriculture_Hall%2C_at_Iowa_State_University.JPG 2x" data-file-width="4000" data-file-height="3000" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Catt_Hall,_previously_known_as_Agriculture_Hall,_at_Iowa_State_University.JPG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Catt Hall, named for <a href="/wiki/Carrie_Chapman_Catt" title="Carrie Chapman Catt">Carrie Chapman Catt</a></div></div></div>
<p>On July 4, 1959, the college was officially renamed Iowa State University of Science and Technology. However, the short-form name "Iowa State University" is used even in official documents such as diplomas.
</p><p>Official names given to the university’s divisions were the College of Agriculture, College of Engineering, College of Home Economics, College of Sciences and Humanities, and College of Veterinary Medicine.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Iowa State's eight colleges today offer more than 100 undergraduate majors and 200 fields of study leading to graduate and professional degrees. The academic program at ISU includes a liberal arts education and some of the world's leading research in the biological and physical sciences.
</p><p>Breakthroughs at Iowa State changing the world are in the areas of human, social, economic, and environmental sustainability;<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> new materials and processes for biomedical as well as industrial applications; nutrition, health, and wellness for humans and animals; transportation and infrastructure; food safety and security; plant and animal sciences; information and decision sciences; and renewable energies. The focus on technology has led directly to many research patents and inventions including the <a href="/wiki/Atanasoff-Berry_Computer" class="mw-redirect" title="Atanasoff-Berry Computer">first binary computer</a> (the ABC), <a href="/wiki/Maytag_blue_cheese" class="mw-redirect" title="Maytag blue cheese">Maytag blue cheese</a>, the round hay baler, and many more.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Located on a 2,000 acres (8.1&#160;km<sup>2</sup>) campus, the university has grown considerably from its roots as an agricultural college and model farm and is recognized internationally today for its comprehensive research programs. It continues to grow and set a new record for enrollment in the fall of 2015 with 36,001 students.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Colleges_and_schools">Colleges and schools</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Colleges and schools">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Iowa State University is organized into eight colleges and two schools that offer 100 Bachelor's degree programs, 112 Masters programs, and 83 Ph.D programs, including one professional degree program in <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State_University_College_of_Veterinary_Medicine" title="Iowa State University College of Veterinary Medicine">Veterinary Medicine</a>.
</p><p>ISU is home to the following schools:
</p>
<ul><li>Greenlee School of Journalism and Mass Communication (within the College of Liberal Arts and Sciences)</li>
<li>School of Education (within the College of Human Sciences)</li></ul>

</td></tr>

<th><i><a href="/wiki/QS_World_University_Rankings" title="QS World University Rankings">QS</a></i><sup id="cite_ref-Rankings_QS_W_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rankings_QS_W-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup>

</th>
<td>301–350
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th><i><a href="/wiki/U.S._News_%26_World_Report" title="U.S. News &amp; World Report">U.S. News &amp; World Report</a></i><sup id="cite_ref-Rankings_USNWR_W_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rankings_USNWR_W-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup>
