<p>Classified as one of <a href="/wiki/Carnegie_Classification_of_Institutions_of_Higher_Education" title="Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education">Carnegie's</a> "R1: Doctoral Universities - Highest Research Activity," Iowa State receives nearly $300 million in research grants each year.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (November 2015)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>The university is one of 62 elected members of the <a href="/wiki/Association_of_American_Universities" title="Association of American Universities">Association of American Universities</a>, an organization composed of the most highly ranked public and private research universities in the U.S. and Canada.
</p><p>In 2016-17 Iowa State university became part of only fifty-four institutions in the U.S. to have earned the "Innovation and Economic Prosperity University" designation by the <a href="/wiki/Association_of_Public_and_Land-grant_Universities" title="Association of Public and Land-grant Universities">Association of Public and Land-grant Universities</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Edelson_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Edelson-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Overall, ISU ranks 111th in the <i><a href="/wiki/U.S._News_%26_World_Report" title="U.S. News &amp; World Report">U.S. News &amp; World Report</a></i> ranking of national universities<sup id="cite_ref-USNWR_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-USNWR-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> and 42nd in the <i><a href="/wiki/Washington_Monthly" title="Washington Monthly">Washington Monthly</a></i> rankings. The agriculture and forestry programs are consistently ranked top 15 in the world by QS. In engineering specialties, at schools whose highest degree is a doctorate, Iowa State's biological/agricultural engineering program is ranked first, the mechanical and civil are ranked 9th and 16th nationally in the U.S. by <i>U.S. News &amp; World Report.</i> Almost all of the engineering specialities at ISU are ranked in the top 30 nationally...<sup id="cite_ref-USNWR_31-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-USNWR-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> ISU's chemistry and physics programs are considered to be some of the best in the world and are ranked in the Top 100 globally and in Top 50 nationally.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup> ISU's Greenlee School of Journalism and Mass Communication is one of the top journalism schools in the country and is notable for being among the first group of accredited journalism and mass communication programs.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup> Greenlee is also cited as one of the leading JMC research programs in the nation, ranked 23rd in a publication by the <a href="/wiki/AEJMC" class="mw-redirect" title="AEJMC">AEJMC</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/National_Science_Foundation" title="National Science Foundation">National Science Foundation</a> ranks ISU 78th in the nation in total research and development expenditures and 94th in research and development expenditures for science and engineering.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup> Currently, ISU ranks second nationally in license and options executed on its intellectual property and #2 nationally in license and options that yield income.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2016)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>In 2016, ISU's landscape architecture program was ranked as the 10th best undergraduate program in the nation, and architecture as the 18th best.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Parks_Library">Parks Library</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Parks Library">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Parks_Library.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Parks_Library.jpg/220px-Parks_Library.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Parks_Library.jpg/330px-Parks_Library.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Parks_Library.jpg/440px-Parks_Library.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1152" data-file-height="768" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Parks_Library.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>W. Robert and Ellen Sorge Parks Library</div></div></div>
<p>The W. Robert and Ellen Sorge Parks Library contains over 2.6 million books and subscribes to more than 98,600 journal titles. Named for W. Robert Parks (1915–2003), the 11th president of Iowa State University, and his wife, Ellen Sorge Parks, the original library was built in 1925 with three subsequent additions made in 1961, 1969, and 1983. The library was dedicated and named after W. Robert and Ellen Sorge Parks in 1984.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Parks Library provides extensive research collections, services and information literacy instruction/information for all students. Facilities consist of the main Parks Library, the e-Library, the Veterinary Medical Library, two subject-oriented reading rooms (design and mathematics), and a remote library storage building.
</p><p>The Library’s extensive collections include electronic and print resources that support research and study for all undergraduate and graduate programs. Nationally recognized collections support the basic and applied fields of biological and physical sciences. The Parks Library includes four public service desks: the Learning Connections Center, the Circulation Desk, the Media Center (including Maps, Media,
Microforms, and Course Reserve collections), and Special Collections. The Library’s instruction program includes a required undergraduate information literacy course as well as a wide variety of subject-based seminars on effective use of Library resources for undergraduate and graduate students.
</p><p>The e-Library, accessed through the Internet, provides access to local and Web-based resources including electronic journals and books, local collections, online indexes, electronic course reserves and guides, and a broad range of subject research guides.
</p><p>Surrounding the first floor lobby staircase in Parks Library are eight mural panels
designed by Iowa artist <a href="/wiki/Grant_Wood" title="Grant Wood">Grant Wood</a>. As with <i>Breaking the Prairie Sod</i>, Wood's other
Iowa State University mural painted two years later, Wood borrowed his theme for <i>When Tillage Begins Other Arts Follow</i> from a speech on <a href="/wiki/Agriculture" title="Agriculture">agriculture</a> delivered by Daniel
Webster in 1840 at the State House in <a href="/wiki/Boston" title="Boston">Boston</a>. Webster said, “When tillage begins, other
arts follow. The farmers therefore are the founders of human civilization.” Wood had
planned to create seventeen mural panels for the library, but only the eleven devoted to
agriculture and the practical arts were completed. The final six, which would have hung
in the main reading room (now the Periodical Room) and were to have depicted the fine
arts, were never begun.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Underground_Comix_Collection">Underground Comix Collection</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Underground Comix Collection">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>The Special Collections Department at the Parks Library houses a collection of <a href="/wiki/Underground_comix" title="Underground comix">underground comix</a> from 1947 to 2007. The collection also consists of correspondences between the Special Collections Department, comic book artists, and dealers.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Intensive_English_and_Orientation_Program">Intensive English and Orientation Program</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Intensive English and Orientation Program">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The university has an IEOP for foreign students. Students whose native language is not English can take IEOP courses to improve their English proficiency to help them succeed at University-level study. IEOP course content also helps students prepare for English proficiency exams, like the TOEFL and IELTS. Classes included in the IEOP include Grammar, Reading, Writing, Oral Communication and Business and various bridge classes.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Distinctions">Distinctions</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Distinctions">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Birthplace_of_first_electronic_digital_computer">Birthplace of first electronic digital computer</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Birthplace of first electronic digital computer">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Atanasoff-Berry_Computer_at_Durhum_Center.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Atanasoff-Berry_Computer_at_Durhum_Center.jpg/220px-Atanasoff-Berry_Computer_at_Durhum_Center.jpg" width="220" height="244" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Atanasoff-Berry_Computer_at_Durhum_Center.jpg/330px-Atanasoff-Berry_Computer_at_Durhum_Center.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Atanasoff-Berry_Computer_at_Durhum_Center.jpg/440px-Atanasoff-Berry_Computer_at_Durhum_Center.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1042" data-file-height="1156" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Atanasoff-Berry_Computer_at_Durhum_Center.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Atanasoff%E2%80%93Berry_Computer" class="mw-redirect" title="Atanasoff–Berry Computer">Atanasoff–Berry Computer</a> replica on 1st floor of Durham Center, Iowa State University.</div></div></div>
<p>Iowa State is the birthplace of the first electronic digital computer, starting the world’s computer technology revolution. Invented by mathematics and physics professor <a href="/wiki/John_Atanasoff" class="mw-redirect" title="John Atanasoff">John Atanasoff</a> and engineering graduate student <a href="/wiki/Clifford_Berry" title="Clifford Berry">Clifford Berry</a> during 1937-42, the <a href="/wiki/Atanasoff-Berry_Computer" class="mw-redirect" title="Atanasoff-Berry Computer">Atanasoff-Berry Computer</a>, or <a href="/wiki/Atanasoff-Berry_Computer" class="mw-redirect" title="Atanasoff-Berry Computer">ABC</a>, pioneered important elements of modern computing, including binary arithmetic, regenerative memory, parallel processing, electronic switching elements, and separation of memory and computer functions.<sup id="cite_ref-auto_15-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On October 19, 1973, U.S. <a href="/wiki/Federal_Judge" class="mw-redirect" title="Federal Judge">Federal Judge</a> <a href="/wiki/Earl_R._Larson" title="Earl R. Larson">Earl R. Larson</a> signed his decision following a lengthy court trial which declared the <a href="/wiki/ENIAC" title="ENIAC">ENIAC</a> patent of Mauchly and Eckert invalid and named Atanasoff the <a href="/wiki/Inventor" title="Inventor">inventor</a> of the electronic digital computer—the Atanasoff-Berry Computer or the ABC.<sup id="cite_ref-auto_15-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>An ABC Team consisting of Ames Laboratory and Iowa State engineers, technicians, researchers and students unveiled a working replica of the Atanasoff-Berry Computer in 1997 which can be seen on display on campus in the Durham Computation Center.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Birth_of_cooperative_extension">Birth of cooperative extension</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Birth of cooperative extension">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Cooperative_extension_service" class="mw-redirect" title="Cooperative extension service">Extension Service</a> traces its roots to farmers’ institutes developed at Iowa State in the late 19th century. Committed to community, Iowa State pioneered the outreach mission of being a land-grant college through creation of the first Extension Service in 1902. In 1906, the <a href="/wiki/Iowa_Legislature" class="mw-redirect" title="Iowa Legislature">Iowa Legislature</a> enacted the Agricultural Extension Act making funds available for demonstration projects. It is believed this was the first specific legislation establishing state extension work, for which Iowa State assumed responsibility. The national extension program was created in 1914 based heavily on the Iowa State model.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Manhattan_Project">Manhattan Project</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Manhattan Project">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>ISU is the only university nationwide that has a <a href="/wiki/U.S._Department_of_Energy" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. Department of Energy">U.S. Department of Energy</a> research laboratory physically located on its campus. Iowa State played a critical role in the development of the <a href="/wiki/Atomic_bomb" class="mw-redirect" title="Atomic bomb">atomic bomb</a> during <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a> as part of the <a href="/wiki/Manhattan_Project" title="Manhattan Project">Manhattan Project</a>, a research and development program begun in 1942 under the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Army_Corps_of_Engineers" title="United States Army Corps of Engineers">U.S. Army Corps of Engineers</a> to develop the atomic bomb.
</p><p>The process to produce large quantities of high-purity uranium metal became known as the <a href="/wiki/Ames_process" title="Ames process">Ames process</a>. One-third of the uranium metal used in the world’s first controlled nuclear chain reaction was produced at Iowa State under the direction of <a href="/wiki/Frank_Spedding" title="Frank Spedding">Frank Spedding</a> and Harley Wilhelm.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> The Ames project received the <a href="/wiki/Army-Navy_%E2%80%98E%E2%80%99_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Army-Navy ‘E’ Award">Army-Navy ‘E’ Award</a> for Excellence in Production on October 12, 1945, signifying two-and-one-half years of excellence in industrial production of metallic uranium as a vital war material. Iowa State is unique among educational institutions to have received this award for outstanding service, an honor normally given to industry.
</p><p>Today, the <a href="/wiki/Ames_Laboratory" title="Ames Laboratory">Ames Laboratory</a> focuses on more peaceful applications of materials research, usually related to increasing energy efficiency. It has broadened the scope of its research into various areas of national concern, including energy resources, high-speed computer design, environmental cleanup and restoration, and the synthesis and study of new materials.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="VEISHEA_celebration">VEISHEA celebration</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: VEISHEA celebration">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/VEISHEA" title="VEISHEA">VEISHEA</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:VEISHEA2006.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/VEISHEA2006.jpg/220px-VEISHEA2006.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/VEISHEA2006.jpg/330px-VEISHEA2006.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/VEISHEA2006.jpg/440px-VEISHEA2006.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1600" data-file-height="1200" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:VEISHEA2006.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>The <a href="/wiki/VEISHEA" title="VEISHEA">VEISHEA</a> 2006 Battle of the Bands</div></div></div>
<p>Iowa State is widely known for VEISHEA, an annual education and entertainment festival that was held on campus each spring. The name VEISHEA was derived from the initials of ISU's five original colleges, forming an acronym as the university existed when the festival was founded in 1922:
</p>
<ul><li><b>V</b>eterinary Medicine</li>
<li><b>E</b>ngineering</li>
<li><b>I</b>ndustrial <b>S</b>cience</li>
<li><b>H</b>ome <b>E</b>conomics</li>
<li><b>A</b>griculture</li></ul>
<p>VEISHEA was the largest student run festival in the nation, bringing in tens of thousands of visitors to the campus each year.
</p><p>The celebration featured an annual parade and many open-house demonstrations of the university facilities and departments. Campus organizations exhibited products, technologies, and held fund raisers for various charity groups. In addition, VEISHEA brought speakers, lecturers, and entertainers to Iowa State, and throughout its over eight decade history, it has hosted such distinguished guests as <a href="/wiki/Bob_Hope" title="Bob Hope">Bob Hope</a>, <a href="/wiki/John_Wayne" title="John Wayne">John Wayne</a>, Presidents <a href="/wiki/Harry_Truman" class="mw-redirect" title="Harry Truman">Harry Truman</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ronald_Reagan" title="Ronald Reagan">Ronald Reagan</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Lyndon_Johnson" class="mw-redirect" title="Lyndon Johnson">Lyndon Johnson</a>, and performers <a href="/wiki/Diana_Ross" title="Diana Ross">Diana Ross</a>, <a href="/wiki/Billy_Joel" title="Billy Joel">Billy Joel</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sonny_and_Cher" class="mw-redirect" title="Sonny and Cher">Sonny and Cher</a>, <a href="/wiki/The_Who" title="The Who">The Who</a>, The <a href="/wiki/Goo_Goo_Dolls" title="Goo Goo Dolls">Goo Goo Dolls</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bobby_V" title="Bobby V">Bobby V</a>, and <a href="/wiki/The_Black_Eyed_Peas" title="The Black Eyed Peas">The Black Eyed Peas</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The 2007 VEISHEA festivities marked the start of Iowa State's year-long <a href="/wiki/Sesquicentennial" class="mw-redirect" title="Sesquicentennial">sesquicentennial</a> celebration.
</p><p>On August 8, 2014, President Steven Leath announced that VEISHEA would no longer be an annual event at Iowa State and the name VEISHEA would be retired.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Research">Research</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Research">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Ames_Laboratory">Ames Laboratory</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Ames Laboratory">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Ames_Lab_logo.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Ames Lab logo.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Ames_Lab_logo.jpg/220px-Ames_Lab_logo.jpg" width="220" height="47" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f1/Ames_Lab_logo.jpg 1.5x" data-file-width="234" data-file-height="50" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Ames_Lab_logo.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div></div></div></div>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/Ames_Laboratory" title="Ames Laboratory">Ames Laboratory</a></div>
<p>Iowa State is the only university nationwide that has a <a href="/wiki/U.S._Department_of_Energy" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. Department of Energy">U.S. Department of Energy</a> research laboratory physically located on its campus. Operated by ISU, the <a href="/wiki/Ames_Laboratory" title="Ames Laboratory">Ames Laboratory</a> is one of ten national DOE Office of Science research laboratories.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>ISU research for the government provided Ames Laboratory its start in the 1940s with the development of a highly efficient process for producing high-purity uranium for atomic energy. Today, Ames Laboratory continues its leading status in current materials research and focuses diverse fundamental and applied research strengths upon issues of national concern, cultivates research talent, and develops and transfers technologies to improve industrial competitiveness and enhance U.S. economic security. Ames Laboratory employs more than 430 full- and part-time employees, including more than 250 scientists and engineers. Students make up more than 20 percent of the paid workforce.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The Ames Laboratory is the U.S. home to 2011 <a href="/wiki/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry" title="Nobel Prize in Chemistry">Nobel Prize in Chemistry</a> winner <a href="/wiki/Dan_Shechtman" title="Dan Shechtman">Dan Shechtman</a> and is intensely engaged with the international scientific community, including hosting a large number of international visitors each year.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="ISU_Research_Park">ISU Research Park</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: ISU Research Park">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The ISU Research Park is a 230-acre development with over 270,000 square feet of building space located just south of the Iowa State campus in Ames. Though closely connected with the university, the research park operates independently to help tenants reach their proprietary goals, linking technology creation, business formation, and development assistance with established technology firms and the marketplace.
</p><p>The ISU Research Park Corporation was established in 1987 as a not-for-profit, independent, corporation operating under a board of directors appointed by Iowa State University and the ISU Foundation. The corporation manages both the Research Park and incubator programs.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Other_research_institutes">Other research institutes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Other research institutes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Iowa State is involved in a number of other significant research and creative endeavors, multidisciplinary collaboration, technology transfer, and strategies addressing real-world problems.
</p><p>In 2010, the <b>Biorenewables Research Laboratory</b> opened in a LEED-Gold certified building that complements and helps replace labs and offices across Iowa State and promotes interdisciplinary, systems-level research and collaboration. The Lab houses the Bioeconomy Institute, the Biobased Industry Center, and the <a href="/wiki/National_Science_Foundation" title="National Science Foundation">National Science Foundation</a> Engineering Research Center for Biorenewable Chemicals, a partnership of six universities as well as the <a href="/wiki/Max_Planck_Society" title="Max Planck Society">Max Planck Society</a> in <a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">Germany</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Technical_University_of_Denmark" title="Technical University of Denmark">Technical University of Denmark</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <b>Engineering Teaching and Research Complex</b> was built in 1999 and is home to Stanley and Helen Howe Hall and Gary and Donna Hoover Hall.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup> The complex is occupied by the to the <a href="/wiki/VRAC" title="VRAC">Virtual Reality Applications Center (VRAC)</a>, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Center_for_Industrial_Research_and_Service&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Center for Industrial Research and Service (page does not exist)">Center for Industrial Research and Service (CIRAS)</a>, Department of Aerospace Engineering and Engineering Mechanics, Department of Materials Science and Engineering, Engineering Computer Support Services, Engineering Distance Education, and Iowa Space Grant Consortium.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_53-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup> And the complex contains one of the world’s only six-sided immersive <a href="/wiki/Virtual_reality" title="Virtual reality">virtual reality</a> labs (C6), as well as the 240 seat 3D-capable Alliant Energy Lee Liu Auditorium, the Multimodal Experience Testbed and Laboratory (METaL), and the User Experience Lab (UX Lab).<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup> All of which supports the research of more than 50 faculty and 200 graduate, undergraduate, and postdoctoral students.<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Campus">Campus</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Campus">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/Campus_of_Iowa_State_University" title="Campus of Iowa State University">Campus of Iowa State University</a></div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Recognition">Recognition</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Recognition">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:ISU_Central_Campus_ASLA_plaque.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/ISU_Central_Campus_ASLA_plaque.jpg/220px-ISU_Central_Campus_ASLA_plaque.jpg" width="220" height="218" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/ISU_Central_Campus_ASLA_plaque.jpg/330px-ISU_Central_Campus_ASLA_plaque.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/ISU_Central_Campus_ASLA_plaque.jpg/440px-ISU_Central_Campus_ASLA_plaque.jpg 2x" data-file-width="768" data-file-height="762" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:ISU_Central_Campus_ASLA_plaque.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>The medallion located in Central Campus, immediately to the west of Curtiss Hall</div></div></div>
<p>Iowa State's campus contains over 160 buildings. Several buildings, as well as the Marston Water Tower, are listed on the <a href="/wiki/National_Register_of_Historic_Places" title="National Register of Historic Places">National Register of Historic Places</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-buildings_56-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-buildings-56">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup> The central campus includes 490 acres (2.0&#160;km<sup>2</sup>) of trees, plants, and classically designed buildings. The landscape's most dominant feature is the 20-acre (81,000&#160;m<sup>2</sup>) central lawn, which was listed as a "medallion site" by the <a href="/wiki/American_Society_of_Landscape_Architects" title="American Society of Landscape Architects">American Society of Landscape Architects</a> in 1999, one of only three central campuses designated as such. The other two were <a href="/wiki/Harvard_University" title="Harvard University">Harvard University</a> and the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Virginia" title="University of Virginia">University of Virginia</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Thomas Gaines, in <i>The Campus As a Work of Art</i>, proclaimed the Iowa State campus to be one of the twenty-five most beautiful campuses in the country. Gaines noted Iowa State's park-like expanse of central campus, and the use of trees and shrubbery to draw together ISU's varied building architecture. Over decades, campus buildings, including the Campanile, Beardshear Hall, and Curtiss Hall, circled and preserved the central lawn, creating a space where students study, relax, and socialize.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Campanile">Campanile</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Campanile">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/Campanile_(Iowa_State_University)" title="Campanile (Iowa State University)">Campanile (Iowa State University)</a></div>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Ames_iowastate.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Ames_iowastate.jpg/170px-Ames_iowastate.jpg" width="170" height="240" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Ames_iowastate.jpg/255px-Ames_iowastate.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Ames_iowastate.jpg/340px-Ames_iowastate.jpg 2x" data-file-width="567" data-file-height="800" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Ames_iowastate.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>The campanile as seen from the north</div></div></div>
<p>The campanile was constructed during 1897-1898 as a <a href="/wiki/Memorial" title="Memorial">memorial</a> to Margaret MacDonald Stanton, Iowa State's first dean of women, who died on July 25, 1895. The tower is located on ISU's central campus, just north of the <a href="/wiki/Memorial_Union_(Iowa_State_University)" title="Memorial Union (Iowa State University)">Memorial Union</a>. The site was selected by Margaret's husband, Edgar W. Stanton, with the help of then-university president William M. Beardshear. The campanile stands 110 feet (34&#160;m) tall on a 16 by 16 foot (5 by 5 m) base, and cost $6,510.20 to construct.<sup id="cite_ref-lib.iastate.edu_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lib.iastate.edu-59">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The campanile is widely seen as one of the major symbols of Iowa State University. It is featured prominently on the university's official ring<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">&#91;60&#93;</a></sup> and the university's mace,<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">&#91;61&#93;</a></sup> and is also the subject of the university's alma mater, <i>The Bells of Iowa State</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-lib.iastate.edu_59-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lib.iastate.edu-59">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Lake_LaVerne">Lake LaVerne</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Lake LaVerne">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Named for Dr. LaVerne W. Noyes, who also donated the funds to see that Alumni Hall could be completed after sitting unfinished and unused from 1905 to 1907. Dr. Noyes is an 1872 alumnus. Lake LaVerne is located west of the <a href="#Memorial_Union">Memorial Union</a> and south of Alumni Hall, <a href="#Carver_Hall">Carver Hall</a>, and <a href="#Music_Hall">Music Hall</a>. The lake was a gift from Dr. Noyes in 1916.
</p><p>Lake LaVerne is the home of two <a href="/wiki/Mute_swan" title="Mute swan">mute swans</a> named Sir Lancelot and Elaine, donated to Iowa State by VEISHEA 1935.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup> In 1944, 1970, and 1971 <a href="/wiki/Cygnet_(bird)" class="mw-redirect" title="Cygnet (bird)">cygnets</a> (baby swans) made their home on Lake LaVerne. Previously Sir Lancelot and Elaine were <a href="/wiki/Trumpeter_swan" title="Trumpeter swan">trumpeter swans</a> but were too aggressive and in 1999 were replaced with two mute swans.
</p><p>In early spring 2003, Lake LaVerne welcomed its newest and most current mute swan duo. In support of Iowa Department of Natural Resources efforts to re-establish the trumpeter swans in Iowa, university officials avoided bringing breeding pairs of male and female mute swans to Iowa State which means the current Sir Lancelot and Elaine are both female.<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">&#91;63&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Reiman_Gardens">Reiman Gardens</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Reiman Gardens">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:RG_Conservatory_Inside.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/RG_Conservatory_Inside.jpg/220px-RG_Conservatory_Inside.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/RG_Conservatory_Inside.jpg/330px-RG_Conservatory_Inside.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/RG_Conservatory_Inside.jpg/440px-RG_Conservatory_Inside.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2272" data-file-height="1704" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:RG_Conservatory_Inside.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Tropical conservatory, <a href="/wiki/Reiman_Gardens" title="Reiman Gardens">Reiman Gardens</a></div></div></div>
<p>Iowa State has maintained a <a href="/wiki/Horticulture" title="Horticulture">horticulture</a> garden since 1914. <a href="/wiki/Reiman_Gardens" title="Reiman Gardens">Reiman Gardens</a> is the third location for these gardens. Today's gardens began in 1993 with a gift from <a href="/wiki/Roy_Reiman" title="Roy Reiman">Bobbi and Roy Reiman</a>. Construction began in 1994 and the Gardens' initial 5 acres (20,000&#160;m<sup>2</sup>) were officially dedicated on September 16, 1995.
</p><p>Reiman Gardens has since grown to become a 14 acres (57,000&#160;m<sup>2</sup>) site consisting of a dozen distinct garden areas, an indoor conservatory and an indoor butterfly "wing", butterfly emergence cases, a gift shop, and several supporting greenhouses. Located immediately south of <a href="/wiki/Jack_Trice_Stadium" title="Jack Trice Stadium">Jack Trice Stadium</a> on the ISU campus, Reiman Gardens is a year-round facility that has become one of the most visited attractions in central Iowa.
</p><p>The Gardens has received a number of national, state, and local awards since its opening, and its <a href="/wiki/Rose_garden" title="Rose garden">rose gardens</a> are particularly noteworthy. It was honored with the President's Award in 2000 by All American Rose Selections, Inc., which is presented to one public garden in the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> each year for superior rose maintenance and display: “For contributing to the public interest in rose growing through its efforts in maintaining an outstanding public rose garden.”<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64">&#91;64&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="University_Museums">University Museums</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: University Museums">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The University Museums consist of the Brunnier Art Museum, Farm House Museum, the Art on Campus Program, the Christian Petersen Art Museum, and the Elizabeth and Byron Anderson Sculpture Garden. The Museums include a multitude of unique exhibits, each promoting the understanding and delight of the visual arts as well as attempt to incorporate a vast interaction between the arts, sciences, and technology.<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">&#91;65&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Brunnier_Art_Museum">Brunnier Art Museum</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: Brunnier Art Museum">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>The Brunnier Art Museum, Iowa’s only accredited museum emphasizing a <a href="/wiki/Decorative_arts" title="Decorative arts">decorative arts</a> collection, is one of the nation's few museums located within a performing arts and conference complex, the <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State_Center" title="Iowa State Center">Iowa State Center</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup> Founded in 1975, the museum is named after its benefactors, Iowa State alumnus Henry J. Brunnier and his wife Ann. The decorative arts collection they donated, called the Brunnier Collection, is extensive, consisting of ceramics, glass, dolls, ivory, jade, and enameled metals.
</p><p>Other fine and decorative art objects from the University Art Collection include prints, paintings, sculptures, textiles, carpets, wood objects, lacquered pieces, silver, and furniture. About eight to 12 annual changing exhibitions and permanent collection exhibitions provide educational opportunities for all ages, from learning the history of a quilt hand-stitched over 100 years ago to discovering how scientists analyze the physical properties of artists' materials, such as glass or stone. Lectures, receptions, conferences, university classes, panel discussions, gallery walks, and gallery talks are presented to assist with further interpretation of objects.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Farm_House_Museum">Farm House Museum</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Farm House Museum">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Farm_House_Museum_south_sign.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Farm_House_Museum_south_sign.jpg/220px-Farm_House_Museum_south_sign.jpg" width="220" height="143" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Farm_House_Museum_south_sign.jpg/330px-Farm_House_Museum_south_sign.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Farm_House_Museum_south_sign.jpg/440px-Farm_House_Museum_south_sign.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1024" data-file-height="667" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Farm_House_Museum_south_sign.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>The Farm House Museum</div></div></div>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/The_Farm_House_(Knapp%E2%80%93Wilson_House)" title="The Farm House (Knapp–Wilson House)">The Farm House (Knapp–Wilson House)</a></div>
<p>Located near the center of the Iowa State campus, the Farm House Museum sits as a monument to early Iowa State history and culture as well as a <a href="/wiki/National_Historic_Landmark" title="National Historic Landmark">National Historic Landmark</a>. As the first building on campus, the Farm House was built in 1860 before campus was occupied by students or even classrooms. The college’s first farm tenants primed the land for agricultural experimentation. This early practice lead to Iowa State Agricultural College and Model Farm opening its doors to Iowa students for free in 1869 under the <a href="/wiki/Morrill_Act_of_1862" class="mw-redirect" title="Morrill Act of 1862">Morrill Act</a> (or Land-grant Act) of 1862.<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Many prominent figures have made the Farm House their home throughout its 150 years of use. The first president of the College, <a href="/wiki/Adonijah_Welch" title="Adonijah Welch">Adonijah Welch</a>, briefly stayed at the Farm House and even wrote his inaugural speech in a bedroom on the second floor. James “Tama Jim” Wilson resided for much of the 1890s with his family at the Farm House until he joined President <a href="/wiki/William_McKinley" title="William McKinley">William McKinley</a>’s cabinet as <a href="/wiki/U.S._Secretary_of_Agriculture" class="mw-redirect" title="U.S. Secretary of Agriculture">U.S. Secretary of Agriculture</a>. Agriculture Dean <a href="/wiki/Charles_Curtiss" title="Charles Curtiss">Charles Curtiss</a> and his young family replaced Wilson and became the longest resident of Farm House.
</p><p>In 1976, over 110 years after the initial construction, the Farm House became a museum after much time and effort was put into restoring the early beauty of the modest farm home. Today, faculty, students, and community members can enjoy the museum while honoring its significance in shaping a nationally recognized land-grant university. Its collection boasts a large collection of 19th and early 20th century decorative arts, furnishings and material culture reflecting Iowa State and Iowa heritage. Objects include furnishings from <a href="/wiki/Carrie_Chapman_Catt" title="Carrie Chapman Catt">Carrie Chapman Catt</a> and Charles Curtiss, a wide variety of quilts, a modest collection of textiles and apparel, and various china and glassware items.
</p><p>As with many sites on the Iowa State University Campus, The Farm House Museum has a few old <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State_Myths_and_Legends" title="Iowa State Myths and Legends">myths and legends</a> associated with it. There are rumors of a ghost changing silverware and dinnerware, unexplained rattling furniture, and curtains that have opened seemingly by themselves.
</p><p>The Farm House Museum is a unique on-campus educational resource providing a changing environment of exhibitions among the historical permanent collection objects that are on display. A walk through the Farm House Museum immerses visitors in the <a href="/wiki/Victorian_era" title="Victorian era">Victorian era</a> (1860-1910) as well as exhibits colorful Iowa and local Ames history.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Art_on_Campus_Collection">Art on Campus Collection</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=27" title="Edit section: Art on Campus Collection">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>Iowa State is home to one of the largest campus public art programs in the United States. Over 2,000 works of public art, including 600 by significant national and international artists, are located across campus in buildings, courtyards, open spaces and offices.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The traditional public art program began during the Depression in the 1930s when Iowa State College’s President Raymond Hughes envisioned that "the arts would enrich and provide substantial intellectual exploration into our college curricula." Hughes invited <a href="/wiki/Grant_Wood" title="Grant Wood">Grant Wood</a> to create the Library’s agricultural murals that speak to the founding of Iowa and Iowa State College and Model Farm. He also offered <a href="/wiki/Christian_Petersen_(sculptor)" title="Christian Petersen (sculptor)">Christian Petersen</a> a one-semester sculptor residency to design and build the fountain and bas relief at the Dairy Industry Building. In 1955, 21 years later, Petersen retired having created 12 major sculptures for the campus and hundreds of small studio sculptures.
</p><p>The Art on Campus Collection is a campus-wide resource of over 2000 public works of art. Programs, receptions, dedications, university classes, Wednesday Walks, and educational tours are presented on a regular basis to enhance visual literacy and aesthetic appreciation of this diverse collection.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Christian_Petersen_Art_Museum">Christian Petersen Art Museum</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=28" title="Edit section: Christian Petersen Art Museum">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Justin_Smith_Morrill_-_Brady-Handy.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Justin_Smith_Morrill_-_Brady-Handy.jpg/170px-Justin_Smith_Morrill_-_Brady-Handy.jpg" width="170" height="232" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Justin_Smith_Morrill_-_Brady-Handy.jpg/255px-Justin_Smith_Morrill_-_Brady-Handy.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Justin_Smith_Morrill_-_Brady-Handy.jpg/340px-Justin_Smith_Morrill_-_Brady-Handy.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2992" data-file-height="4080" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Justin_Smith_Morrill_-_Brady-Handy.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Justin_Smith_Morrill" title="Justin Smith Morrill">Justin Smith Morrill</a>, namesake of Morrill Hall</div></div></div>
<p>The Christian Petersen Art Museum in <a href="/wiki/Morrill_Hall_(Iowa_State_University)" title="Morrill Hall (Iowa State University)">Morrill Hall</a> is named for the nation’s first permanent campus artist-in-residence, <a href="/wiki/Christian_Petersen_(sculptor)" title="Christian Petersen (sculptor)">Christian Petersen</a>, who sculpted and taught at Iowa State from 1934 through 1955, and is considered the founding artist of the Art on Campus Collection.
</p><p>Named for <a href="/wiki/Justin_Smith_Morrill" title="Justin Smith Morrill">Justin Smith Morrill</a> who created the <a href="/wiki/Morrill_Land-Grant_Colleges_Act" class="mw-redirect" title="Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act">Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act</a>, Morrill Hall was completed in 1891. Originally constructed to fill the capacity of a library, museum, and chapel, its original uses are engraved in the exterior stonework on the east side. The building was vacated in 1996 when it was determined unsafe and was also listed in the <a href="/wiki/National_Register_of_Historic_Places" title="National Register of Historic Places">National Register of Historic Places</a> the same year. In 2005, $9 million was raised to renovate the building and convert it into a museum. Completed and reopened in March 2007, Morrill Hall is home to the Christian Petersen Art Museum.
</p><p>As part of University Museums, the Christian Petersen Art Museum at Morrill Hall is the home of the Christian Petersen Art Collection, the Art on Campus Program, the University Museums’s Visual Literacy and Learning Program, and Contemporary Changing Art Exhibitions Program.
</p><p>Located within the Christian Petersen Art Museum are the Lyle and Nancy Campbell Art Gallery, the Roy and Bobbi Reiman Public Art Studio Gallery, the Margaret Davidson Center for the Study of the Art on Campus Collection, the Edith D. and Torsten E. Lagerstrom Loaned Collections Center, and the Neva M. Petersen Visual Learning Gallery. University Museums shares the James R. and Barbara R. Palmer Small Objects Classroom in Morrill Hall.<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Anderson_Sculpture_Garden">Anderson Sculpture Garden</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=29" title="Edit section: Anderson Sculpture Garden">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>The Elizabeth and Byron Anderson Sculpture Garden is located by the Christian Petersen Art Museum at historic Morrill Hall. The <a href="/wiki/Sculpture_garden" title="Sculpture garden">sculpture garden</a> design incorporates sculptures, a gathering arena, and sidewalks and pathways. Planted with perennials, ground cover, shrubs, and flowering trees, the landscape design provides a distinctive setting for important works of 20th and 21st century sculpture, primarily American. Ranging from forty-four inches to nearly nine feet high and from bronze to other metals, these works of art represent the richly diverse character of modern and contemporary sculpture.<sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">&#91;70&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The sculpture garden is adjacent to Iowa State’s 22 acres (89,000&#160;m<sup>2</sup>) central campus. Adonijah Welch, ISU’s first president, envisioned a picturesque campus with a winding road encircling the college’s majestic buildings, vast lawns of green grass, many varieties of trees sprinkled throughout to provide shade, and shrubbery and flowers for fragrance. Today, the central lawn continues to be an iconic place for all Iowa Staters, and enjoys national acclaim as one of the most beautiful campuses in the country. The new Elizabeth and Byron Anderson Sculpture Garden further enhances the beauty of Iowa State.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sustainability">Sustainability</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=30" title="Edit section: Sustainability">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Iowa State's composting facility "can handle more than 10,000 tons of organic wastes annually."<sup id="cite_ref-ISU_promotes_sustainability_via_an_all-university_compost_facility._71-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ISU_promotes_sustainability_via_an_all-university_compost_facility.-71">&#91;71&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-New_web_site_charts_campus_building_energy_use_72-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-New_web_site_charts_campus_building_energy_use-72">&#91;72&#93;</a></sup> The school's new $3 million revolving loan fund loans money for energy efficiency and conservation projects on campus.<sup id="cite_ref-Live_Green_revolving_loan_fund_73-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Live_Green_revolving_loan_fund-73">&#91;73&#93;</a></sup> In the 2011 College Sustainability Report Card issued by the Sustainable Endowments Institute, the university received a B grade.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74">&#91;74&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Student_life">Student life</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: Student life">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Residence_halls">Residence halls</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=32" title="Edit section: Residence halls">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Roberts_Residence_Hall_Iowa_State_University.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Roberts_Residence_Hall_Iowa_State_University.jpg/220px-Roberts_Residence_Hall_Iowa_State_University.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Roberts_Residence_Hall_Iowa_State_University.jpg/330px-Roberts_Residence_Hall_Iowa_State_University.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Roberts_Residence_Hall_Iowa_State_University.jpg/440px-Roberts_Residence_Hall_Iowa_State_University.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1600" data-file-height="1200" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Roberts_Residence_Hall_Iowa_State_University.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>View looking east towards Roberts Hall</div></div></div>
<p>Iowa State operates 20 on-campus <a href="/wiki/Dormitory" title="Dormitory">residence halls</a>. The residence halls are divided into geographical areas.
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Buildings_of_Iowa_State_University#Union_Drive" class="mw-redirect" title="Buildings of Iowa State University">Union Drive Association</a>
(UDA) consists of four residence halls located on the west side of campus, including <a href="/wiki/Buildings_of_Iowa_State_University#Friley_Hall" class="mw-redirect" title="Buildings of Iowa State University">Friley Hall</a>, which has been declared one of the largest residence halls in the country.<sup id="cite_ref-friley_75-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-friley-75">&#91;75&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Buildings_of_Iowa_State_University#Richardson_Court" class="mw-redirect" title="Buildings of Iowa State University">Richardson Court Association</a> (RCA) consists of 12 residence halls on the east side of campus.
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Buildings_of_Iowa_State_University#Towers" class="mw-redirect" title="Buildings of Iowa State University">Towers Residence Association</a> (TRA) are located south of the main campus. Two of the four towers, Knapp and Storms Halls, were imploded in 2005; however, Wallace and Wilson Halls still stand.
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Buildings_of_Iowa_State_University#Buchanan_Hall" class="mw-redirect" title="Buildings of Iowa State University">Buchanan Hall</a> and <a href="/wiki/Buildings_of_Iowa_State_University#Geoffroy_Hall" class="mw-redirect" title="Buildings of Iowa State University">Geoffroy Hall</a> are nominally considered part of the RCA, despite their distance from the other buildings.
</p><p>ISU operates four apartment complexes for upperclassmen, <a href="/wiki/Buildings_of_Iowa_State_University#Frederiksen_Court" class="mw-redirect" title="Buildings of Iowa State University">Frederiksen Court</a>, <a href="/wiki/Buildings_of_Iowa_State_University#Schilletter/University_Village" class="mw-redirect" title="Buildings of Iowa State University">SUV Apartments</a>, Legacy Tower, and Maricopa, the latter two being leased by the university.
</p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Student_government">Student government</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: Student government">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The governing body for ISU students is ISU Student Government. The ISU Student Government is composed of a president, vice president, finance director, cabinet appointed by the president, a clerk appointed by the vice president, senators representing each college and residence area at the university, a nine-member judicial branch and an election commission.<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">&#91;76&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Student_organizations">Student organizations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=34" title="Edit section: Student organizations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Memorial_Union_east.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/50/Memorial_Union_east.jpg/220px-Memorial_Union_east.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/50/Memorial_Union_east.jpg/330px-Memorial_Union_east.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/50/Memorial_Union_east.jpg/440px-Memorial_Union_east.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1025" data-file-height="683" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Memorial_Union_east.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Memorial Union</div></div></div>
<p>ISU has over 800 student organizations on campus that represent a variety of interests. Organizations are supported by Iowa State's Student Activities Center. Many student organization offices are housed in the <a href="/wiki/Memorial_Union_(Iowa_State_University)" title="Memorial Union (Iowa State University)">Memorial Union</a>.
</p><p>The Memorial Union at Iowa State University opened in September 1928 and is currently home to a number of University departments and student organizations, a bowling alley, the University Book Store, and the Hotel Memorial Union.
</p><p>The original building was designed by architect, William T. Proudfoot. The building employs a classical style of <a href="/wiki/Architecture" title="Architecture">architecture</a> reflecting <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title="Ancient Greece">Greek</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ancient_Rome" title="Ancient Rome">Roman</a> influences. The building's design specifically complements the designs of the major buildings surrounding the University's Central Campus area, Beardshear Hall to the west, Curtiss Hall to the east, and MacKay Hall to the north. The style utilizes columns with <a href="/wiki/Corinthian_order" title="Corinthian order">Corinthian</a> capitals, Paladian windows, triangular <a href="/wiki/Pediments" class="mw-redirect" title="Pediments">pediments</a>, and formally balanced <a href="/wiki/Facades" class="mw-redirect" title="Facades">facades</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Designed to be a living memorial for ISU students lost in <a href="/wiki/World_War_I" title="World War I">World War I</a>, the building includes a solemn memorial hall, named the Gold Star Room, which honors the names of the dead World War I, <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a>, <a href="/wiki/Korean_War" title="Korean War">Korean</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vietnam_War" title="Vietnam War">Vietnam</a>, and <a href="/wiki/War_on_Terrorism" class="mw-redirect" title="War on Terrorism">War on Terrorism</a> veterans engraved in marble. Symbolically, the hall was built directly over a library (the Browsing Library) and a small chapel, the symbol being that no country would ever send its young men to die in a war for a noble cause without a solid foundation on both education (the library) and religion (the chapel).
</p><p>Renovations and additions have continued through the years to include: elevators, bowling lanes, a parking ramp, a book store, food court, and additional wings.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Music">Music</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=35" title="Edit section: Music">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The Choral Division of the Department of Music and Theater at Iowa State University consists of over 400 choristers in four main ensembles – the <i>Iowa State Singers</i>, <i>Cantamus,</i> the <i>Iowa Statesmen</i>, and <i>Lyrica</i> – and multiple small ensembles including three a cappella groups, <i>Count Me In</i> (female), <i>Shy of a Dozen</i> (male), and "Hymn and Her" (co-ed).
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Greek_community">Greek community</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=36" title="Edit section: Greek community">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>ISU is home to an active <a href="/wiki/Fraternities_and_sororities" title="Fraternities and sororities">Greek community</a>. There are 50 chapters that involve 14.6 percent of undergraduate students. Collectively, <a href="/wiki/Fraternities_and_sororities" title="Fraternities and sororities">fraternity</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sorority" class="mw-redirect" title="Sorority">sorority</a> members have raised over $82,000 for philanthropies and committed 31,416 hours to community service. In 2006, the ISU Greek community was named the best large Greek community in the <a href="/wiki/Midwestern_United_States" title="Midwestern United States">Midwest</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">&#91;78&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The ISU Greek Community has received multiple Jellison and Sutherland Awards from Association for Fraternal Leadership and Values, formerly the Mid-American Greek Council Association. These awards recognize the top Greek Communities in the Midwest.
</p>
