<p>The first fraternity, <a href="/wiki/Delta_Tau_Delta" title="Delta Tau Delta">Delta Tau Delta</a>, was established at Iowa State in 1875, six years after the first graduating class entered Iowa State. The first sorority, I.C. Sorocis, was established only two years later, in 1877. I.C. Sorocis later became a chapter of the first national sorority at Iowa State, <a href="/wiki/Pi_Beta_Phi" title="Pi Beta Phi">Pi Beta Phi</a>. Anti-Greek rioting occurred in 1888. As reported in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Des_Moines_Register" title="The Des Moines Register">The Des Moines Register</a></i>, "The anti-secret society men of the college met in a mob last night about 11 o'clock in front of the society rooms in chemical and physical hall, determined to break up a joint meeting of three secret societies." In 1891, President William Beardshear banned students from joining secret college fraternities, resulting in the eventual closing of all formerly established fraternities. President Storms lifted the ban in 1904.<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Following the lifting of the fraternity ban, the first thirteen national fraternities (IFC) installed on the Iowa State campus between 1904 and 1913 were, in order, <a href="/wiki/Sigma_Nu" title="Sigma Nu">Sigma Nu</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sigma_Alpha_Epsilon" title="Sigma Alpha Epsilon">Sigma Alpha Epsilon</a>, <a href="/wiki/Beta_Theta_Pi" title="Beta Theta Pi">Beta Theta Pi</a>, <a href="/wiki/Phi_Gamma_Delta" title="Phi Gamma Delta">Phi Gamma Delta</a>, <a href="/wiki/Alpha_Tau_Omega" title="Alpha Tau Omega">Alpha Tau Omega</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kappa_Sigma" title="Kappa Sigma">Kappa Sigma</a>, <a href="/wiki/Theta_Xi" title="Theta Xi">Theta Xi</a>, <a href="/wiki/Acacia_Fraternity" class="mw-redirect" title="Acacia Fraternity">Acacia</a>, <a href="/wiki/Phi_Sigma_Kappa" title="Phi Sigma Kappa">Phi Sigma Kappa</a>, <a href="/wiki/Delta_Tau_Delta" title="Delta Tau Delta">Delta Tau Delta</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pi_Kappa_Alpha" title="Pi Kappa Alpha">Pi Kappa Alpha</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Phi_Delta_Theta" title="Phi Delta Theta">Phi Delta Theta</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup> Though some have suspended their chapters at various times, eleven of the original thirteen fraternities were active in 2008. Many of these chapters existed on campus as local fraternities before being reorganized as national fraternities, prior to 1904.
</p><p>In the Spring of 2014, it was announced that <a href="/wiki/Alpha_Phi" title="Alpha Phi">Alpha Phi</a> Sorority would be coming to Iowa state in the Fall of 2014, with <a href="/wiki/Delta_Gamma" title="Delta Gamma">Delta Gamma</a> Sorority Following in the near future.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="School_newspaper">School newspaper</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=37" title="Edit section: School newspaper">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State_Daily" title="Iowa State Daily">Iowa State Daily</a></div>
<p>The <i>Iowa State Daily</i> is the university's student newspaper. The <i>Daily</i> has its roots from a news sheet titled the <i>Clipper</i>, which was started in the spring of 1890 by a group of students at Iowa Agricultural College led by F.E. Davidson. The <i>Clipper</i> soon led to the creation of the <i>Iowa Agricultural College Student</i>, and the beginnings of what would one day become the <i>Iowa State Daily</i>. It was awarded the 2016 Best All-Around Daily Student Newspaper by the Society of Professional Journalists.<sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84">&#91;84&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Campus_radio">Campus radio</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=38" title="Edit section: Campus radio">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/KURE" title="KURE">KURE</a></div>
<p>88.5 KURE is the university's student-run radio station. Programming for KURE includes ISU sports coverage, talk shows, the annual quiz contest Kaleidoquiz, and various music genres.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Student_television">Student television</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=39" title="Edit section: Student television">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>ISUtv is the university's student-run television station. It is housed in the former WOI-TV station that was established in 1950. The student organization of ISUtv has many programs including Newswatch, a twice weekly news spot, Cyclone InCyders, the campus sports show, Fortnightly News, a satirical/comedy program, and Cy's Eyes on the Skies, a twice weekly weather show.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Athletics">Athletics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=40" title="Edit section: Athletics">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State_Cyclones" title="Iowa State Cyclones">Iowa State Cyclones</a></div>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Big_12_logo_in_Iowa_State_colors.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Big_12_logo_in_Iowa_State_colors.svg/220px-Big_12_logo_in_Iowa_State_colors.svg.png" width="220" height="130" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Big_12_logo_in_Iowa_State_colors.svg/330px-Big_12_logo_in_Iowa_State_colors.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Big_12_logo_in_Iowa_State_colors.svg/440px-Big_12_logo_in_Iowa_State_colors.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="270" data-file-height="160" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Big_12_logo_in_Iowa_State_colors.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Big_12_Conference" title="Big 12 Conference">Big 12 Conference</a> logo</div></div></div>
<p>The "Cyclones" name dates back to 1895. That year, Iowa suffered an unusually high number of devastating cyclones (as <a href="/wiki/Tornado" title="Tornado">tornadoes</a> were called at the time). In September, Iowa Agricultural College's football team traveled to <a href="/wiki/Northwestern_University" title="Northwestern University">Northwestern University</a> and defeated that team by a score of 36-0. The next day, the <i><a href="/wiki/Chicago_Tribune" title="Chicago Tribune">Chicago Tribune</a>'</i>s headline read "Struck by a Cyclone: It Comes from Iowa and Devastates Evanston Town."<sup id="cite_ref-isutimeline1875_85-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-isutimeline1875-85">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup> The article began, "Northwestern might as well have tried to play football with an Iowa cyclone as with the Iowa team it met yesterday." The nickname stuck.
</p><p>The school colors are <a href="/wiki/Cardinal_(color)" title="Cardinal (color)">cardinal</a> and <a href="/wiki/Gold_(color)" title="Gold (color)">gold</a>. The mascot is <a href="/wiki/Cy_the_Cardinal" title="Cy the Cardinal">Cy the Cardinal</a>, introduced in 1954. Since a cyclone was determined to be difficult to depict in costume, the cardinal was chosen in reference to the school colors. A contest was held to select a name for the mascot, with the name Cy being chosen as the winner.
</p><p>The Iowa State Cyclones are a member of the <a href="/wiki/Big_12_Conference" title="Big 12 Conference">Big 12 Conference</a> and compete in <a href="/wiki/NCAA" class="mw-redirect" title="NCAA">NCAA</a> <a href="/wiki/Division_I_(NCAA)" class="mw-redirect" title="Division I (NCAA)">Division I</a> <a href="/wiki/Football_Bowl_Subdivision" class="mw-redirect" title="Football Bowl Subdivision">Football Bowl Subdivision</a> (FBS), fielding 16 varsity teams in 12 sports. The Cyclones also compete in and are a founding member of the <a href="/wiki/Central_States_Collegiate_Hockey_League" title="Central States Collegiate Hockey League">Central States Collegiate Hockey League</a> of the <a href="/wiki/American_Collegiate_Hockey_Association" title="American Collegiate Hockey Association">American Collegiate Hockey Association</a>.
</p><p>Iowa State's intrastate <a href="/wiki/College_rivalry" title="College rivalry">archrival</a> is the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Iowa" title="University of Iowa">University of Iowa</a> with whom it competes annually for the <a href="/wiki/Iowa_Corn_Cy-Hawk_Series" title="Iowa Corn Cy-Hawk Series">Iowa Corn Cy-Hawk Series</a> trophy, an annual athletic competition between the two schools. Sponsored by the Iowa Corn Growers Association, the competition includes all head-to-head regular season competitions between the two rival universities in all sports.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Football">Football</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=41" title="Edit section: Football">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State_Cyclones_football" title="Iowa State Cyclones football">Iowa State Cyclones football</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Jack_trice_stadium_south_endzone.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Jack_trice_stadium_south_endzone.jpg/220px-Jack_trice_stadium_south_endzone.jpg" width="220" height="124" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Jack_trice_stadium_south_endzone.jpg/330px-Jack_trice_stadium_south_endzone.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Jack_trice_stadium_south_endzone.jpg/440px-Jack_trice_stadium_south_endzone.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4160" data-file-height="2340" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Jack_trice_stadium_south_endzone.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Jack_Trice_Stadium" title="Jack Trice Stadium">Jack Trice Stadium</a></div></div></div>
<p>Football first made its way onto the Iowa State campus in 1878 as a recreational sport, but it was not until 1892 that Iowa State organized its first team to represent the school in football. In 1894, college president William M. Beardshear spearheaded the foundation of an athletic association to officially sanction Iowa State football teams. The 1894 team finished with a 6-1 mark.<sup id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-86">&#91;86&#93;</a></sup> The Cyclones compete each year for traveling trophies. Since 1977, Iowa State and Iowa compete annually for the <a href="/wiki/Cy-Hawk_Trophy" class="mw-redirect" title="Cy-Hawk Trophy">Cy-Hawk Trophy</a>. Iowa State competes in an <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State%E2%80%93Kansas_State_football_rivalry" title="Iowa State–Kansas State football rivalry">annual rivalry game</a> against <a href="/wiki/Kansas_State_University" title="Kansas State University">Kansas State</a> known as Farmageddon and against former conference foe <a href="/wiki/University_of_Missouri" title="University of Missouri">Missouri</a> for the <a href="/wiki/Telephone_Trophy" class="mw-redirect" title="Telephone Trophy">Telephone Trophy</a>. The main rival is the <a href="/wiki/Iowa%E2%80%93Iowa_State_football_rivalry" title="Iowa–Iowa State football rivalry">Iowa Hawkeyes</a>. Unfortunately for Iowa State, this competition has not gone well in recent years. The Hawkeyes have won the last four games. Nevertheless, this rivalry has provided excitement for fans from Ames and Iowa City alike.
</p>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:MattCampbellISU2016.jpeg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4c/MattCampbellISU2016.jpeg/220px-MattCampbellISU2016.jpeg" width="220" height="330" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4c/MattCampbellISU2016.jpeg/330px-MattCampbellISU2016.jpeg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4c/MattCampbellISU2016.jpeg/440px-MattCampbellISU2016.jpeg 2x" data-file-width="3291" data-file-height="4936" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:MattCampbellISU2016.jpeg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Head coach <a href="/wiki/Matt_Campbell_(American_football_coach)" title="Matt Campbell (American football coach)">Matt Campbell</a></div></div></div>
<p>The Cyclones play their home games at <a href="/wiki/Jack_Trice_Stadium" title="Jack Trice Stadium">Jack Trice Stadium</a>, named after <a href="/wiki/Jack_Trice" title="Jack Trice">Jack Trice</a>, ISU's first <a href="/wiki/African-American" class="mw-redirect" title="African-American">African-American</a> athlete and also the first and only Iowa State athlete to die from injuries sustained during athletic competition. Trice died three days after his first game playing for Iowa State against <a href="/wiki/University_of_Minnesota" title="University of Minnesota">Minnesota</a> in <a href="/wiki/Minneapolis,_Minnesota" class="mw-redirect" title="Minneapolis, Minnesota">Minneapolis</a> on October 6, 1923. Suffering from a broken collarbone early in the game, he continued to play until he was trampled by a group of Minnesota players. It is disputed whether he was trampled purposely or if it was by accident. The stadium was named in his honor in 1997 and is the only NCAA Division I-A stadium named after an African-American.<sup id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87">&#91;87&#93;</a></sup> Jack Trice Stadium, formerly known as Cyclone Stadium, opened on September 20, 1975, with a win against the <a href="/wiki/Air_Force_Academy" class="mw-redirect" title="Air Force Academy">Air Force Academy</a>.
</p>
<h3><span id="Men.27s_basketball"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Men's_basketball">Men's basketball</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=42" title="Edit section: Men&#039;s basketball">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State_Cyclones_men%27s_basketball" title="Iowa State Cyclones men&#39;s basketball">Iowa State Cyclones men's basketball</a></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Hilton_Coliseum_Inside_View.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Hilton_Coliseum_Inside_View.jpg/220px-Hilton_Coliseum_Inside_View.jpg" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Hilton_Coliseum_Inside_View.jpg/330px-Hilton_Coliseum_Inside_View.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Hilton_Coliseum_Inside_View.jpg/440px-Hilton_Coliseum_Inside_View.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2576" data-file-height="1716" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Hilton_Coliseum_Inside_View.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Hilton_Coliseum" title="Hilton Coliseum">Hilton Coliseum</a></div></div></div>
<p>Hopes of "Hilton Magic" returning took a boost with the hiring of ISU alum, Ames native, and fan favorite <a href="/wiki/Fred_Hoiberg" title="Fred Hoiberg">Fred Hoiberg</a> as coach of the men's basketball team in April 2010. Hoiberg ("The Mayor") played three seasons under legendary coach <a href="/wiki/Johnny_Orr_(basketball,_born_1927)" title="Johnny Orr (basketball, born 1927)">Johnny Orr</a> and one season under future <a href="/wiki/Chicago_Bulls" title="Chicago Bulls">Chicago Bulls</a> coach <a href="/wiki/Tim_Floyd" title="Tim Floyd">Tim Floyd</a> during his standout collegiate career as a Cyclone (1991–95). Orr laid the foundation of success in men's basketball upon his arrival from <a href="/wiki/University_of_Michigan" title="University of Michigan">Michigan</a> in 1980 and is credited with building Hilton Magic. Besides Hoiberg, other Cyclone greats played for Orr and brought winning seasons, including <a href="/wiki/Jeff_Grayer" title="Jeff Grayer">Jeff Grayer</a>, <a href="/wiki/Barry_Stevens_(basketball)" title="Barry Stevens (basketball)">Barry Stevens</a>, and walk-on <a href="/wiki/Jeff_Hornacek" title="Jeff Hornacek">Jeff Hornacek</a>. The 1985-86 Cyclones were one of the most memorable. Orr coached the team to second place in the <a href="/wiki/Big_Eight_Conference" title="Big Eight Conference">Big Eight</a> and produced one of his greatest career wins, a victory over his former team and No. 2 seed <a href="/wiki/University_of_Michigan" title="University of Michigan">Michigan</a> in the second round of the <a href="/wiki/NCAA_Men%27s_Division_I_Basketball_Tournament" class="mw-redirect" title="NCAA Men&#39;s Division I Basketball Tournament">NCAA tournament</a>.
</p><p>Under coaches Floyd (1995–98) and <a href="/wiki/Larry_Eustachy" title="Larry Eustachy">Larry Eustachy</a> (1998–2003), Iowa State achieved even greater success. Floyd took the Cyclones to the Sweet Sixteen in 1997 and Eustachy led ISU to two consecutive <a href="/wiki/Big_12_Conference" title="Big 12 Conference">Big 12</a> regular season conference titles in 1999-2000 and 2000–01, plus the conference tournament title in 2000. Seeded No. 2 in the 2000 NCAA tournament, Eustachy and the Cyclones defeated <a href="/wiki/UCLA" class="mw-redirect" title="UCLA">UCLA</a> in the Sweet Sixteen before falling to <a href="/wiki/Michigan_State_University" title="Michigan State University">Michigan State</a>, the eventual NCAA Champion, in the regional finals by a score of 75-64 (the differential representing the <a href="/wiki/Michigan_State_Spartans" title="Michigan State Spartans">Spartans</a>' narrowest margin of victory in the tournament). Standout <a href="/wiki/Marcus_Fizer" title="Marcus Fizer">Marcus Fizer</a> and <a href="/wiki/Jamaal_Tinsley" title="Jamaal Tinsley">Jamaal Tinsley</a> were scoring leaders for the Cyclones who finished the season 32-5. Tinsley returned to lead the Cyclones the following year with another conference title and No. 2 seed, but ISU finished the season with a 25-6 overall record after a stunning loss to No. 15 seed <a href="/wiki/Hampton_University" title="Hampton University">Hampton</a> in the first round.
</p><p>In 2011-12, Hoiberg's Cyclones finished third in the Big 12 and returned to the NCAA Tournament, dethroning defending national champion <a href="/wiki/University_of_Connecticut" title="University of Connecticut">Connecticut</a>, 77-64, in the second round before losing in the Round of 32 to top-seeded <a href="/wiki/University_of_Kentucky" title="University of Kentucky">Kentucky</a>. All-Big 12 First Team selection <a href="/wiki/Royce_White" title="Royce White">Royce White</a> led the Cyclones with 38 points and 22 rebounds in the two contests, ending the season at 23-11.
</p><p>The 2013-14 campaign turned out to be another highly successful season. Iowa State went 28-8, won the Big 12 Tournament, and advanced to the Sweet Sixteen by beating <a href="/wiki/North_Carolina_Tar_Heels" title="North Carolina Tar Heels">North Carolina</a> in the second round of the NCAA Tournament. The Cyclones finished 11-7 in Big 12 play, finishing in a tie for third in the league standings, and beat a school-record nine teams (9-3) that were ranked in the Associated Press top 25. The Cyclones opened the season 14-0, breaking the school record for consecutive wins. <a href="/wiki/Melvin_Ejim" title="Melvin Ejim">Melvin Ejim</a> was named the Big 12 Player of the Year and an All-American by five organizations. Deandre Kane was named the Big 12 Tournament’s most valuable player.
</p><p>On June 8, 2015, Steve Prohm took over as head basketball coach replacing Hoiberg who left to take the head coaching position with the Chicago Bulls. In his first season with the Cyclones, Prohm secured a #4 seed in the Midwest region where the Cyclones advanced to the Sweet Sixteen before falling to top-seeded <a href="/wiki/University_of_Virginia" title="University of Virginia">Virginia</a>, 84-71. In 2017, Iowa State stunned 3rd ranked <a href="/wiki/University_of_Kansas" title="University of Kansas">Kansas</a>, 92-89, in overtime, snapping KU’s 54-game home winning streak, before winning the <a href="/wiki/2017_Big_12_Men%27s_Basketball_Tournament" title="2017 Big 12 Men&#39;s Basketball Tournament">2017 Big 12 Men's Basketball Tournament</a>, its third conference championship in four years, defeating <a href="/wiki/West_Virginia_University" title="West Virginia University">West Virginia</a> in the final.
</p><p>Of Iowa State's 16 NCAA Tournament appearances, the Cyclones have reached the Sweet Sixteen six times (1944, 1986, 1997, 2000, 2014, 2016), made two appearances in the Elite Eight (1944, 2000), and reached the Final Four once in 1944.<sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88">&#91;88&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span id="Women.27s_basketball"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Women's_basketball">Women's basketball</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=43" title="Edit section: Women&#039;s basketball">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State_Cyclones_women%27s_basketball" title="Iowa State Cyclones women&#39;s basketball">Iowa State Cyclones women's basketball</a></div>
<p>Iowa State is known for having one of the most successful women's basketball programs in the nation. Since the founding of the Big 12, Coach <a href="/wiki/Bill_Fennelly" title="Bill Fennelly">Bill Fennelly</a> and the Cyclones have won three conference titles (one regular season, two tournament), and have advanced to the Sweet Sixteen five times (1999–2001, 2009, 2010) and the Elite Eight twice (1999, 2009) in the NCAA Tournament. The team has one of the largest fan bases in the nation with attendance figures ranked third in the nation in 2009, 2010, and 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89">&#91;89&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-11-12attendance_90-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11-12attendance-90">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Volleyball">Volleyball</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=44" title="Edit section: Volleyball">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Coach Christy Johnson-Lynch led the 2012 Cyclones team to a fifth straight 20-win season and fifth NCAA regional semifinal appearance in six seasons, and leading Iowa State to a 22-8 (13-3 Big 12) overall record and second-place finish in the conference. The Cyclones finished the season with seven wins over top-25 teams, including a victory over No. 1 <a href="/wiki/Nebraska_Cornhuskers_women%27s_volleyball" title="Nebraska Cornhuskers women&#39;s volleyball">Nebraska Cornhuskers</a> in Iowa State’s first-ever win over a top-ranked opponent in addition to providing the only Big 12 Conference loss to the 2012 conference and NCAA champion <a href="/wiki/Texas_Longhorns_women%27s_volleyball" title="Texas Longhorns women&#39;s volleyball">Texas Longhorns</a>.
</p><p>In 2011, Iowa State finished the season 25-6 (13-3 Big 12), placing second in the league, as well as a final national ranking of eighth. 2011 is only the second season in which an Iowa State volleyball team has ever recorded 25 wins. The Cyclones beat No. 9 <a href="/wiki/University_of_Florida" title="University of Florida">Florida</a> during the season in <a href="/wiki/Gainesville,_Florida" title="Gainesville, Florida">Gainesville</a>, its sixth win over a top-10 team in Cyclone history. In 2009, Iowa State finished the season second in the Big 12 behind Texas with a 27-5 record and ranked No. 6, its highest ever national finish.
</p><p>Johnson-Lynch is the fastest Iowa State coach to clinch 100 victories. In 2011, she became the school’s winningest volleyball coach when her team defeated the <a href="/wiki/Texas_Tech_Red_Raiders_volleyball" class="mw-redirect" title="Texas Tech Red Raiders volleyball">Texas Tech Red Raiders</a>, her 136th coaching victory, in straight sets.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Wrestling">Wrestling</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=45" title="Edit section: Wrestling">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/Iowa_State_Cyclones_wrestling" title="Iowa State Cyclones wrestling">Iowa State Cyclones wrestling</a></div>
<p>The ISU wrestling program has captured the NCAA wrestling tournament title eight times between 1928 and 1987,<sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">&#91;91&#93;</a></sup> and won the Big 12 Conference Tournament three consecutive years, 2007-2009. On February 7, 2010, the Cyclones became the first collegiate wrestling program to record its 1,000th dual win in program history by defeating the <a href="/wiki/Arizona_State_Sun_Devils_wrestling" class="mw-redirect" title="Arizona State Sun Devils wrestling">Arizona State Sun Devils</a>, 30-10, in Tempe, Arizona.
</p><p>In 2002, under former NCAA champion &amp; Olympian Coach <a href="/wiki/Bobby_Douglas" title="Bobby Douglas">Bobby Douglas</a>, Iowa State became the first school to produce a four-time, <b>undefeated</b> NCAA Division I champion, <a href="/wiki/Cael_Sanderson" title="Cael Sanderson">Cael Sanderson</a> (considered by the majority of the wrestling community to be the best college wrestler ever),<sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92">&#91;92&#93;</a></sup> who also took the gold medal at the 2004 <a href="/wiki/Olympic_Games" title="Olympic Games">Olympic Games</a> in <a href="/wiki/Athens,_Greece" class="mw-redirect" title="Athens, Greece">Athens</a>, <a href="/wiki/Greece" title="Greece">Greece</a>. <a href="/wiki/Dan_Gable" title="Dan Gable">Dan Gable</a>, another legendary ISU wrestler, is famous for having lost only one match in his entire Iowa State collegiate career - his last - and winning gold at the 1972 Olympics in <a href="/wiki/Munich,_Germany" class="mw-redirect" title="Munich, Germany">Munich</a>, <a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">Germany</a>, while not giving up a single point.
</p><p>In 2013, Iowa State hosted its eighth NCAA Wrestling Championships. The Cyclones hosted the first NCAA championships in 1928.
</p><p>In February 2017, former <a href="/wiki/Virginia_Tech_University" class="mw-redirect" title="Virginia Tech University">Virginia Tech</a> coach and 2016 NWCA Coach of the Year <a href="/wiki/Kevin_Dresser" title="Kevin Dresser">Kevin Dresser</a> was introduced as the new Cyclone wrestling coach, replacing <a href="/wiki/Kevin_Jackson" title="Kevin Jackson">Kevin Jackson</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-93" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93">&#91;93&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notable_alumni_and_faculty">Notable alumni and faculty</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Iowa_State_University&amp;action=edit&amp;section=46" title="Edit section: Notable alumni and faculty">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">main article: <a href="/wiki/List_of_Iowa_State_University_people" title="List of Iowa State University people">List of Iowa State University people</a></div>
<p>Since its inception in 1858, Iowa State has fostered excellence in its alumni, under the instruction of world-class faculty. These people include astronauts, scientists, Pulitzer Prize winners, statesmen, academicians, CEOs, entrepreneurs, athletes, film and television actors, and a host of other notable individuals in their respective fields.
</p>
